<font color="#FF0000">CLINTONÇS PLANS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb 19  7:31:05 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
   After watching the explanations by our government leaders about why we must bomb Iraq, I can summarize ClintonÇs arguments for his actions as follows:<br><br>
   Saddam Hussein is a very dangerous man, who has no scruples about killing his own people to stay in power and would be willing to use his chemical and biological weapons to attack his neighbors.  No argument.<br><br>
   When we bomb Iraq, Saddam Hussein will not be targeted, and our goals do not include his removal.  Civilians will be unavoidably killed by our bombing because there are laws against killing political leaders, so civilians are the only ligitimate targets.  It is not against the law to kill them if they get in the way of the bombs.<br><br>
   After being bombed, the surviving civilians are supposed to become angry at Saddam Hussein (not at us) and change their government.  They must do this even though there are no fair elections, and people who open their mouths to say something against their leader are immediately done away with.  When Saddam kills them, the United States will claim that it is an internal affair of Iraq.  If they do not succeed in removing Saddam anyway, then we will return to bomb again and again without ever expecting to get rid of Saddam or to find all of his weapons. In this way, we will make the world secure in the future.<br><br>
   Other targets of the bombs will be the chemical and biological weapons, the locations of which we do not know because Saddam would not let our inspectors look for them.  We have &quot;smart bombs&quot;, however, which may be able to find the weapons in some way.  Clinton refused to serve in the Vietnam War, so he is not quite sure how bombs work.  However, he has confidence that they will be able to destroy the weapons through good luck.  He refused to serve in Vietnam because, according to him, that war was &quot;immoral&quot;, but wars he is not expected to fight in are not immoral.  He claims to have been correct in protesting the war because he knew better than the five consecutive American presidents who thought Vietnam was vital to American interests.  People should not protest his war because the President is the elected Chief-of-State in a democracy and should always be obeyed.<br><br>
   The chemical and biological weapons are very dangerous, and the smallest amounts of them can kill a person.  Therefore, we are going to blow them up, allowing the clouds of smoke to drift wherever the wind takes them - perhaps over Kuwait, Turkey, Russia, or even over our own forces, as the clouds of chemical weapons that we blew up in the Gulf War apparently did.<br><br>
   Finally, Clinton promises to make sure that the veterans have proper hospitalization, training, and employment after the war, although Vietnam and Gulf War veterans were promised the same things and are still waiting.<br><br>
   Does anyone have any problems following the logic of these arguments?  I certainly do.  On November 10 of this year, it will be exactly 30 years since I received my honorable discharge from the Air Force after flying more than 1800 hours in combat out of a total of almost 3200 hours in nearly five years of active duty.  I am still trying to find my first job in the United States.  I can find work in almost any country except the United States.  Every time my name appears first on a Federal civil service list, the selection is cancelled.  Of all Vietnam Era veterans who appear first on such lists, 71% are passed over by ClintonÇs government.  It was ClintonÇs people, the ones who managed his campaign, who were calling me and my fellow veterans &quot;baby killers&quot; and worse.  Our patriotic servicemen who are ready to do their duty and risk their lives in this new war on the legitimate orders from the President should know what they have to look forward to in the future.  It would comfort me to see some effective laws passed before they are sent to make sure that they do not have the same experiences as Vietnam and Gulf War veterans are still having when they return home, but there is no talk of passing laws to protect these future veterans.
